h <i>tre(f)</i> ‘homestead, settlement’ + a mutated form of <i>mawr</i> ‘large’.","Irish (Dublin and Down): variant of   Trower  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trower","meanings":["English (mainly Sussex and Surrey): variant of   Thrower  .","Irish (Leitrim): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Treabhair</b> ‘descendant of <i>Treabhar</i>’, a byname meaning ‘industrious, prudent’. The name has been Anglicized as   Trevor  .","Americanized form of German <b>Trauer</b>, a habitational name for someone from Trauen in Lower Saxony."]},{"name":"Trover","meanings":["Possibly Irish: from <b>Trower</b>, a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Treabhair</b> (see   Trevor  )."]},{"name":"Traver","meanings":["French: unexplained.","Catalan: habitational name from any of the minor places called Traver, mainly in La Garrotxa and L'Empordà districts.","English: variant of   Trevor  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Adda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of several old German names beginning with <i>Ed-</i>. The Elder and Younger <i>Eddas</i> are also the names of two influential Old Icelandic books of Norse myths and poems."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Goch","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Italian <b>Rocco</b>; ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]},{"name":"Ieuaf","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adda Goch ap Ieuaf of Trevor was born in 1325, in Trevor, Llangollen, Denbighshire, Wales, his father, Ieuaf ap Adda, was 30 and his mother, Myfanwy verch Madog, was 91. He had at least 1 son and 5 daughters with Angharad ferch Daffydd. He died in 1356, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1325–1356":"1325–1356","1270–1356":"1270–1356","1320–1416":"1320–1416","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1323–Female":"1323–Surnud","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1347–1416":"1347–1416","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1349":"1349","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1356":"1356","1235":"1235","1323":"1323","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1416":"1416","Treforest, Rhondda Cynon Taff, Wales":"Treforest, Rhondda Cynon Taf, Wales, United Kingdom","Trefor, Llangollen, Denbigh, Wales":"Trevor, Llangollen, Denbighshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1325–1356":"1325–1356","1270–1356":"1270–1356","1320–1416":"1320–1416","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1323–Female":"1323–Kuollut","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1347–1416":"1347–1416","1349–Female":"1349–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1356":"1356","1235":"1235","1323":"1323","1320":"1320","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","1416":"1416","Treforest, Rhondda Cynon Taff, Wales":"Treforest, Rhondda Cynon Taf, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Trefor, Llangollen, Denbigh, Wales":"Trevor, Llangollen, Denbighshir